\section*{2.3 Multiplication, division and combined operations of integers}

\subsection*{Sign rules for multiplication/division}

\begin{itemize}
\item Same signs $\Rightarrow$ \textbf{positive}
  \begin{itemize}
  \item Example: $(-6)\times(-2)=+12$
  \end{itemize}
\item Different signs $\Rightarrow$ \textbf{negative}
  \begin{itemize}
  \item Example: $(-6)\times 2=-12$
  \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\noindent Same rules for division:
\begin{itemize}
\item $(-48)\div(-6)=+8$
\item $45\div(-9)=-5$
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Powers (indices) with negatives}

Be careful with brackets.
\begin{itemize}
\item $(-3)^2 = 9$ (because the negative is inside the square)
\item $-3^2 = -(3^2) = -9$ (square happens first, then the minus)
\end{itemize}

\noindent\textbf{Useful idea:} brackets tell you what is being powered.

\subsection*{Roots}

\begin{itemize}
\item $\sqrt{81}=9$
\item $\sqrt[3]{-125}=-5$ (cube root keeps the sign)
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Order of operations (BODMAS)}

This is the order you calculate in:
\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{B}rackets
\item \textbf{O}rders (powers, roots)
\item \textbf{D}ivision and \textbf{M}ultiplication (left to right)
\item \textbf{A}ddition and \textbf{S}ubtraction (left to right)
\end{enumerate}

\noindent\textbf{Example}
\[
3+5\times(-2)-18\div(-3)
\]
Do $\times$ and $\div$ first:
\begin{itemize}
\item $5\times(-2)=-10$
\item $18\div(-3)=-6$
\end{itemize}
So:
\[
3+(-10)-(-6)=3-10+6=-1
\]

\subsection*{Brackets can change the value}

\begin{itemize}
\item $5+4\times3=5+12=17$
\item $(5+4)\times3=9\times3=27$
\end{itemize}

\vspace{1em}
\noindent\textbf{Practice Questions}
