\section*{2.4 Rational numbers, irrational numbers and real numbers}

\subsection*{Rational numbers (numbers you can write as a fraction)}

A \textbf{rational number} can be written as $\dfrac{a}{b}$ where $a,b$ are integers and $b\neq 0$.

\noindent These include:
\begin{itemize}
\item Integers: $-4, 0, 7$
\item Fractions: $\frac{2}{5}$
\item Terminating decimals: $0.72$
\item Recurring decimals: $0.\overline{3}$
\end{itemize}

\noindent\textbf{Examples}
\begin{itemize}
\item $0.72=\frac{72}{100}=\frac{18}{25}$
\item $0.\overline{3}=\frac13$
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Terminating vs recurring decimals}

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Terminating}: ends (like $0.125$)
\item \textbf{Recurring}: repeats a pattern forever (like $0.41\overline{6}$)
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Irrational numbers (cannot be written as a fraction)}

These cannot be written exactly as a fraction, and their decimals go on forever \textbf{without repeating}.

\noindent Common examples:
\begin{itemize}
\item $\pi$
\item $\sqrt{2}$, $\sqrt{5}$ (when the number under the square root is \emph{not} a perfect square)
\end{itemize}

\noindent\textbf{Examples}
\begin{itemize}
\item $\sqrt{50}=\sqrt{25\times 2}=5\sqrt{2}$ is irrational because $\sqrt{2}$ is irrational.
\item $\sqrt{16}=4$ is rational (perfect square).
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Real numbers}

\textbf{Real numbers} include \emph{all} rational and irrational numbers.

\noindent So:
\begin{itemize}
\item rational numbers $\subset$ real numbers
\item irrational numbers $\subset$ real numbers
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Comparing surds (like $\sqrt{5}$)}

You can compare by knowing nearby squares:
\begin{itemize}
\item $2^2=4$, $3^2=9$ so $\sqrt{5}$ is between 2 and 3.
\item Roughly, $\sqrt{5}\approx 2.24$ (good enough for ordering).
\end{itemize}

