\section*{2.5 Operations on real numbers}

This section is mainly about doing calculations correctly with:
\begin{itemize}
\item fractions
\item mixed numbers
\item decimals
\item negatives
\item and sometimes roots
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Converting between mixed and improper fractions}

\begin{itemize}
\item Mixed number $\rightarrow$ improper:
\[
2\frac56=\frac{2\times 6+5}{6}=\frac{17}{6}
\]
\item Improper $\rightarrow$ mixed: divide top by bottom.
\[
\frac{17}{12}=1\frac{5}{12}
\]
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Simplifying fractions}

Divide top and bottom by the same number.
\begin{itemize}
\item $\frac{18}{24}$ divide by 6 $\Rightarrow \frac34$
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Adding/subtracting fractions}

You need a \textbf{common denominator}.
\begin{itemize}
\item $\frac34+\frac25=\frac{15}{20}+\frac{8}{20}=\frac{23}{20}$
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Multiplying fractions}

Multiply tops, multiply bottoms, then simplify.
\begin{itemize}
\item $\frac{3}{8}\times\frac{5}{6}=\frac{15}{48}=\frac{5}{16}$
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Dividing fractions}

Flip the second fraction (take the reciprocal), then multiply.
\begin{itemize}
\item $\frac{3}{8}\div\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)=\frac{3}{8}\times 4=\frac{3}{2}$
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Decimals with negatives}

Treat them like positive or negative numbers and combine carefully.
\begin{itemize}
\item $0.008-(-1.02)=0.008+1.02=1.028$
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{``Halfway between two numbers''}

Halfway means ``average of the two numbers'':
\[
\text{halfway}=\frac{\text{first}+\text{second}}{2}
\]
Example:
\[
\text{halfway between } -6 \text{ and } 5=\frac{-6+5}{2}=-\frac12
\]

